<h2>Examples Of High-Protein Low-Carb Foods</h2>
The best part about this diet plan is that it is sure to consist of some of your favorite food varieties that you neednâ€™t refrain from. Here are some of the most popular foods that are low in carbs and high in protein:
<h3>1. Meat And Fish:</h3>
All you meat lovers â€“ rejoice! Hereâ€™s a diet plan that promotes the consumption of many protein-packed meat and fish varieties. These include turkey and chicken breast, lamb, steak, ham, veal, pork tenderloin, minced beef, prawns, shrimps, crab, tuna, salmon, etc. Though you must limit your intake of meat rich in saturated fats such as pork, lamb and beef, you can enjoy one portion of fish, white meat, as well as lean meat every day. They provide a good dose of protein while also protecting you from the dangers of saturated fats â€“ like heart diseases.
<h3>2. Nuts And Seeds:</h3>
Looking for a healthy snack to fight those hunger pangs? Youâ€™ll be happy to know that your go-to fillers are excellent protein powerhouses! Almonds, walnuts, pistachios, pumpkin, flax and sunflower seeds are rich in protein and can be eaten straight as snacks or can be used to top salads and smoothies. Just ensure that you keep the portion sizes of these nuts and seeds small as they are high in fats (the good fats).[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][vc_widget_sidebar sidebar_id="healthy_nutrition___food_sidebar"][/vc_column][/vc_row]";s:10:"post_title";s:48:"5 Amazing Benefits Of High Protein Low Carb Diet";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:48:"5-amazing-benefits-of-high-protein-low-carb-diet";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2017-04-20 12:06:40";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2017-04-20 12:06:40";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:41:"http://localhost/homemadesolutions/?p=597";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:1;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"598";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"1";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2017-04-07 12:20:22";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2017-04-07 12:20:22";s:12:"post_content";s:1597:"[vc_row][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_column_text]So, what kind of foods can give you the optimal amount of Methionine you need? And why is this Methionine so necessary? If these are the questions that you have, then this is the post you must check out!

Read on and find out about Methionine, its uses, side effects and most importantly, what are the commonly found foods that contain Methionine.
<h2>What Is Methionine?</h2>
Methionine is an amino acid; the basic block that links up with other amino acids and bonds to form protein. Methionine isnâ€™t produced in the body, and it helps in the formation of cartilages. Methionine is also quite essential for many cell functions. It helps prevent hair loss and strengthens your nails.
<h2>Uses:</h2>
Methionine has other uses, apart from helping in the formation of cartilages (<a href="http://www.webmd.com/vitamins-supplements/ingredientmono-42-methionine.aspx?activeingredientid=42&amp;activeingredientname=methionine" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">2</a>). Some of them include:
<ul>
 	<li>Increases acidity of urine</li>
 	<li>Improves wound healing</li>
 	<li>Treats acetaminophen (Tylenol) poisoning</li>
 	<li>Treats liver disorders</li>
</ul>
<em><strong>Other Possible Uses:</strong></em>
<ul>
 	<li>Treats depression</li>
 	<li>Alcoholism</li>
 	<li>Allergies</li>
 	<li>Asthma</li>
 	<li>Copper poisoning</li>
 	<li>Radiation side effects</li>
 	<li>Schizophrenia</li>
</ul>
